  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by moving it through complex sequences of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and has been amended to strengthen measures against such activities. The law outlines strict guidelines and penalties for individuals and institutions involved in money laundering, emphasizing the need for financial institutions to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures. \n\nInternationally, money laundering is also recognized as a serious crime, with organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** setting global standards for combating it. Countries that fail to adequately address money laundering may face economic and political consequences, including sanctions or restrictions in international financial systems.",
